abstract: Marina Gross, the American interpreter during President Trump’s meeting with President Vladimir V. Putin of Russia, is facing calls from Congress to testify.
snippet: Marina Gross, the American interpreter during President Trump’s meeting with President Vladimir V. Putin of Russia, is facing calls from Congress to testify.
lead_paragraph: WASHINGTON — Marina Gross, the only other American in the room during President Trump’s meeting on Monday with President Vladimir V. Putin of Russia, was the interpreter for Laura Bush at the Russian resort of Sochi in 2008 and interpreted for former Secretary of State Rex W. Tillerson in Moscow in 2017. She appears to live in an apartment in Arlington, Va., is an employee of the State Department and is, unsurprisingly, fluent in Russian.

abstract: The carefully crafted narrative around Brett Kavanaugh, President Trump’s Supreme Court nominee, plays down his legacy as a charter member of elite Washington.
snippet: The carefully crafted narrative around Brett Kavanaugh, President Trump’s Supreme Court nominee, plays down his legacy as a charter member of elite Washington.
lead_paragraph: When Judge Brett M. Kavanaugh introduced himself to the American people on Monday, with a beaming President Trump beside him, he had a lot to say about his mother, a former high school teacher and a Maryland judge. He accorded his father strikingly less attention — just 34 words, compared with 132 about his mother — mentioning his “unparalleled work ethic” while not saying exactly what work he did.

abstract: By forcing a showdown last year, Democrats gave Republicans an opening to end the filibuster of Supreme Court nominees. Some wish they had it back.
snippet: By forcing a showdown last year, Democrats gave Republicans an opening to end the filibuster of Supreme Court nominees. Some wish they had it back.
lead_paragraph: WASHINGTON — In the days leading up to the vote on Judge Neil M. Gorsuch’s confirmation to the Supreme Court in the spring of 2017, Senator Susan Collins approached Senator Michael Bennet on the Senate floor with an urgent plea.

abstract: On Thursday, Twitter began slashing tens of millions of suspicious accounts from users’ followers, after mounting skepticism from advertisers and users about the accuracy of the company’s most visible measure of popularity.

byline_original: By Richard Harris, Gabriel J.X. Dance and Danny DeBelius

abstract: In representing the porn star Stormy Daniels, the lawyer thinks he can bring down a president — one cable-news appearance at a time.
snippet: In representing the porn star Stormy Daniels, the lawyer thinks he can bring down a president — one cable-news appearance at a time.
lead_paragraph: The attorney Michael Avenatti stands just under six feet tall, with blatant blue eyes and thinning hair he shaves down to stubble, exposing the crumpled vein at his left temple. Before February, when he agreed to represent Stephanie Clifford — the pornographic film performer better known as Stormy Daniels — in her legal battle with the president of the United States, Avenatti was in the best shape of his life: 185 pounds, 9 percent body fat. The ever-expanding pressures of the case have meant less time at the gym, and in recent months he has lost some muscle weight. But his cheeks and chin remain Cubist in their geometry, and in motion, head lowered and shoulders hunched, he still has the bearing of a light-heavyweight brawler.

abstract: At a Montana Trump rally, there was mockery of #MeToo and the “fake news” media and bragging about breaking records for drawing crowds.
snippet: At a Montana Trump rally, there was mockery of #MeToo and the “fake news” media and bragging about breaking records for drawing crowds.
lead_paragraph: President Trump does not express much affection for celebrities, which is unsurprising considering how many of them have vocally, even profanely, repudiated his policies.

abstract: A life’s value can be determined by the culpability of the officer, the sympathy for the victim, and even where the people lived.
snippet: A life’s value can be determined by the culpability of the officer, the sympathy for the victim, and even where the people lived.
lead_paragraph: When a police officer fatally shoots a person, there are usually reasons offered: The officer was afraid for his life. The victim was reaching for his waistband or refused to show his hands. A glint looked like a gun.
